<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38038a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38038a">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38038a"> 38(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ joyday</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Letters to the Editor</b> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Miss Brown of the original cake shop (1638) wrote to me a short time ago, knowing I was interested in the folk-lore of cookery, and she says: &ldquo;Special interest seems to be in the long history of the Banbury cake, and the possibility of a still longer previous history which takes us back to very early times. The shape is not usual, and just as <mark>the cradle shape for mince pies is the oldest</mark>, and which we still continue to use here, so the elliptical shape of the Banbury cake may mean something particularly interesting connected with some specially <mark>joyous feast</mark>.&rdquo; <small> <a name="MP24may30" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MP24may30"><cite title="source">Morning Post</cite></a> (24 May 1930) 6/4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
